Title:
Hiding Malicious Code with Module Stomping (Part 2)

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post continues F-Secure’s research into “module stomping,” a Windows in-memory evasion technique where an attacker loads a legitimate DLL/module and overwrites its mapped image with malicious code.  
- It focuses on practical implementation details and tradeoffs versus classic process injection patterns (e.g., RWX allocations, remote thread creation) that are commonly monitored by EDR.  
- The technique aims to make malicious code appear to originate from a legitimate, signed module and to reduce suspicious memory artifacts by reusing existing module-backed regions.  
- It discusses Windows loader/PE considerations (sections, protections, relocations/imports) and how to execute the stomped payload reliably.  
- Useful for red teamers, implant developers, and malware analysts evaluating stealthy in-memory execution, and for blue teams building detections around anomalous module memory and image integrity.  
- It’s interesting because it highlights detection gaps when defenders over-rely on “new memory allocation + execute” heuristics and don’t validate module-backed memory content.

Technical Focus:
- Module stomping / DLL image overwrite
- Windows PE loading semantics (sections, relocations, imports)
- Memory protection changes (VirtualProtect) and executable mappings
- Thread start / execution transfer (e.g., APC/thread context/entrypoint redirection)
- EDR detection surface: module-backed memory integrity vs allocation-based heuristics

Use Cases:
- Develop stealthier in-memory payload execution that blends into legitimate module mappings
- Compare module stomping against process hollowing, reflective loading, and classic shellcode injection
- Create detection logic for “image-backed region modified” and mismatched PE headers/sections
- Build lab PoCs to test EDR telemetry around module loads and post-load memory writes

Keywords:
module stomping, process injection, Windows loader, DLL, PE format, image mapping, VirtualProtect, WriteProcessMemory, memory forensics, EDR evasion, code cave, section permissions, relocations, IAT, entry point, APC, thread context, signed module, image integrity, in-memory execution